+# Architecture Decision: Unified EventBus for Notification System
+
+## Decision
+
+All inter-service event communication uses the **EventBus** (`src/events/event-bus.ts`).
+The notification system previously used a mix of EventBus (for `order:created`) and
+CallbackRegistry (for `order:status-changed`). This has been unified so that both event
+types flow through the EventBus.
+
+## Why EventBus over CallbackRegistry
+
+| Criterion | EventBus | CallbackRegistry |
+|---|---|---|
+| Coupling | Loose — producers and consumers share only event types | Tighter — services share a global registry instance |
+| Async support | Native (`emit` returns `Promise`) | Synchronous only |
+| Debugging | Built-in event log (`getEventLog()`) for replay/inspection | No history |
+| Typed events | Discriminated union in `event-types.ts` | Generic `<T>` parameter |
+| Extensibility | New subscribers added without touching producers | Same, but no central type catalog |
+
+The EventBus was already the dominant pattern, documented as the intended architecture,
+and supported richer capabilities. Unifying on it eliminates the question of "which
+pattern do I use?" for future developers.
+
+## How to add a new event
+
+1. Define the event interface in `src/events/event-types.ts`
+2. Add it to the `AppEvent` union type
+3. Emit it via `this.eventBus.emit({ type: 'your:event', ... })` in the producing service
+4. Subscribe via `this.eventBus.on<YourEvent>('your:event', handler)` in the consuming service
+
+## CallbackRegistry
+
+The generic `CallbackRegistry` class is retained in `src/utils/callback-registry.ts` as a
+utility. It is appropriate for lightweight, synchronous callback patterns that are not
+part of the inter-service event system (e.g., UI hooks, simple observer plumbing). It
+should **not** be used for notification triggers or cross-service communication.
